This one measures about 1.2 meters to the flower spike tip; while culms reach 120 cm, the flower spike itself is compact and narrow, 30 cm long and 3 mm wide. I have seen this same taxon used as a landscaping species, e.g. for commercial development on Stagecoach Road. In any case this grass is well adapted and perhaps naturalized at this point. The shinier adaxial blade and duller abaxial blade are shown in photo two with the hand model.

name: Poaceae
rights: Copyright c michael hogan, licensed under a Creative Commons cc_by_nc_sa_name license: http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/
occurrenceRemarks: Seen along one of the main trails in a ruderal area at the trailside. The smooth culms and their cauline leaves were dried, but new basal green leaves have begun to appear. Several dozen of these tuftgrass specimens were seen closely arrayed, with most total plant heights being in the range of seventy to ninety cm. There is a single terminal spike on each culm, with the spike height being about four cm. Spikelets are densely packed into the cylindrical spike. Culm nodes are slightly enlarged, and joints are slightly offset from 180 degrees....namely approximately 175 degrees. Cauline leaves are about 20 cm in length and basal leaves are about 35 cm. This colony of grasses is clearly not being cultivated, but is well naturalized.

name: Quercus wislizeni
rights: Copyright c michael hogan, licensed under a Creative Commons cc_by_nc_sa_name license: http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/
occurrenceRemarks: Small shrub in mesic soils about 90 cm high, but estimated age of about seven years. Favor the taxon Quercus chrysolepis over Q. agrifolia, because: (1) small stature and small leaf size; (2) leaf form flatter rather than the exaggerated convex shape of agrifolia; (3) stems more golden brown rather than the greyish of agrifolia; (4) stem branching angles (about 50 degrees) and branching frequency match chrysolepis rather than agrifolia.
